<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1436,1932,2031]" box="[199,1436,2004,2031]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,470,2004,2031]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Venezuelan species, recognized by the combination of small size (ca. 2.31
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,153,251]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
mm), the pronotum with very shallow impressions and rather uniform punctation, the pronotal shape, the very large black spots on the elytra, and the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[720,806,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1841,1866]" captionTargetBox="[202,1397,292,1788]" captionTargetId="figure@43.[151,1435,273,1817]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 24. Hydrochus pictus n. sp., habitus and male genitalia of holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3587231" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3587231/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
; described below). Differentiation from other similarly small sized species with similarly shaped pronotum will require dissection of males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
